the decline of the manufacturing industry and the rising employment in the services sector continues.</p><p>In May, for the first time in Australia’s history, there were more people employed in the professional, scientific and technical services industry than in manufacturing. It also won’t be very long until the number employed in manufacturing is surpassed by those working in the education and training industry:<b><br></b></p>  <figure class=\"element element-embed\" data-alt=\"Employment by industry\">  <iframe src=\"http://cf.datawrapper.de/odj3t/3/\" frameborder=\"0\" allowtransparency=\"true\"allowfullscreen=\"allowfullscreen\" webkitallowfullscreen=\"webkitallowfullscreen\"mozallowfullscreen=\"mozallowfullscreen\" oallowfullscreen=\"oallowfullscreen\"msallowfullscreen=\"msallowfullscreen\" width=\"480\" height=\"400\"></iframe> </figure>  <p>Since 2002, manufacturing has gone from the biggest employer to now the fifth biggest behind health care, retail trade, construction and now professional, scientific and technical services.</p><p>The decline of manufacturing is part of a long-term trend that has seen our economy become much broader – and shifted from making things to more services oriented. Thirty years ago a third of the workforce was employed in agriculture, mining, manufacturing, electricity and gas or the construction industries; now it is about 23%.<b><br></b></p><p>Along with this long-term trend, however ,has been the change to the labour market that has occurred during and after the mining boom. The second mining boom took off in 2009 when iron ore prices rose by more than 30% in a year. It led to a boom in investment that peaked in September 2012.<b><br></b></p><p>It took a few months in 2009 for the industry to react to the increase in prices, but by August 2009 the drop in mining employment that occurred during the GFC had begun to turn around. Thus to see the impact of both the boom and since its end we can look at employment growth in each industry from August 2009 to August 2012, and the growth since August 2012:<b><br></b></p>  <figure class=\"element element-embed\" data-alt=\"Employment growth by industry during and after the mining boom\">  <iframe src=\"http://cf.datawrapper.de/bQQLT/5/\" frameborder=\"0\" allowtransparency=\"true\"allowfullscreen=\"allowfullscreen\" webkitallowfullscreen=\"webkitallowfullscreen\"mozallowfullscreen=\"mozallowfullscreen\" oallowfullscreen=\"oallowfullscreen\"msallowfullscreen=\"msallowfullscreen\" width=\"480\" height=\"400\"></iframe> </figure>  <p>From 2009 to 2012, employment in the mining industry soared nearly 70%. It left all other<b><br></b></p><p>industries well behind. But employment in most industries did grow during this period. Five industries, however, experienced a decline in employment – agriculture, manufacturing, transport and postal, wholesale trade, and construction. </p><p>The change since the end of the boom is quite stark. Since the second half of 2012, employment in mining has actually fallen. The biggest growth industry is the nebulous “other services”; the big growth sector in this industry was in “repair and maintenance services” .<b><br></b></p><p>But of the five industries that declined in employment during the boom, only two have continued to fall since August 2012: wholesale trade and manufacturing. The big falls in the wholesale trade sector have occurred in the grocery, liquor and tobacco product wholesaling sector and, not coincidentally given the drop in the manufacturing industry and the end of the mining investment boom, in the machinery and equipment wholesaling sector. In the manufacturing industry the losses were across the board, with only wood products manufacturing surviving relatively unscathed.<b><br></b></p><p>It’s worth noting the industry to shrink the most employees since 2012 is the information media and telecommunications industry. And it will neither please nor surprise any of my colleagues to discover the biggest contributor to this loss has been in publishing, which includes newspaper and magazine publishing.<b><br></b></p><p>In light of the decline in employment in the mining industry perhaps the biggest surprise in the past year has been the strong jobs growth in both Western Australia and Queensland:</p>  <figure class=\"element element-embed\" data-alt=\"Annual employment growth by state\">  <iframe src=\"http://cf.datawrapper.de/TjPC7/3/\" frameborder=\"0\" allowtransparency=\"true\"allowfullscreen=\"allowfullscreen\"webkitallowfullscreen=\"webkitallowfullscreen\"mozallowfullscreen=\"mozallowfullscreen\"oallowfullscreen=\"oallowfullscreen\"msallowfullscreen=\"msallowfullscreen\" width=\"480\" height=\"400\"></iframe> </figure>  <p>Aside from the large growth in Northern Territory (which comes off a small base of just 130,000 workers) both WA and Queensland have been the strong performers over the past year. But the two states are performing well for different reasons. In WA, the housing boom which has seen house prices in Perth increase by 14% in the past two years (second only to Sydney) has also seen employment in the rental, hiring and real estat<b><br></b></p><p>industry growth the most in the past 12 months. Highlighting the change in the mining economy since 2012, although employment in WA is growing as well as any other state, employment in mining in WA in the past year has fallen by 5%. </p>  <figure class=\"element element-embed\" data-alt=\"WA and QLD annual employment growth\">  <iframe src=\"http://cf.datawrapper.de/pTKR4/2/\" frameborder=\"0\" allowtransparency=\"true\"allowfullscreen=\"allowfullscreen\"webkitallowfullscreen=\"webkitallowfullscreen\"mozallowfullscreen=\"mozallowfullscreen\"oallowfullscreen=\"oallowfullscreen\"msallowfullscreen=\"msallowfullscreen\" width=\"480\" height=\"400\"></iframe> </figure>  <p>In Queensland, however, mining employment continues to grow. So, too, in Queensland does employment in manufacturing – making it, with South Australia, the only state to observe an increase in manufacturing employment in the past 12 months. The difference in employment in mining jobs in Queensland and WA highlights the different sectors of the industry:<b><br></b></p>  <figure class=\"element element-embed\" data-alt=\"Mining employment\">  <iframe src=\"http://cf.datawrapper.de/4QVnc/1/\" frameborder=\"0\" allowtransparency=\"true\"allowfullscreen=\"allowfullscreen\"webkitallowfullscreen=\"webkitallowfullscreen\"mozallowfullscreen=\"mozallowfullscreen\" oallowfullscreen=\"oallowfullscreen\"msallowfullscreen=\"msallowfullscreen\" width=\"480\" height=\"400\"></iframe> <figcaption>WA</figcaption> </figure>  <p>The decline in mining jobs in WA matches the fall in investment, and yet Queensland mining jobs appear to buck this connection. That is mostly because the growth sectors of the industry have changed. From 2009 to 2012 the boom in jobs was in the metal ore mining sector – the increase of 40,000 jobs in that sector accounted for nearly half of all new mining jobs in that time:<b><br></b></p>  <figure class=\"element element-embed\" data-alt=\"Mining industry employment growth\">  <iframe src=\"http://cf.datawrapper.de/gNfVX/2/\" frameborder=\"0\" allowtransparency=\"true\"allowfullscreen=\"allowfullscreen\"webkitallowfullscreen=\"webkitallowfullscreen\"mozallowfullscreen=\"mozallowfullscreen\" oallowfullscreen=\"oallowfullscreen\"msallowfullscreen=\"msallowfullscreen\" width=\"480\" height=\"400\"></iframe> </figure>  <p>Since 2012, however, the biggest growth sector in the industry has been in oil and gas extraction. As I noted in March, coal seam gas exploration and production in Queensland is cranking up in order to begin a massive boost in exports over the next few years. But it would be folly to hope that coal seam gas will directly lead to a boom in overall employment. Oil and gas extraction accounts for only about 9% of all mining employment.<b><br></b></p><p>While the boom of 2009-2012 brought more jobs in mining, the future for employment in Australia looks set to be in the services sector as the health, professional and education sectors continue to grow.<b><br></b></p>","headline":"Services sector jobs go ahead in leaps and bounds after mining boom","trailText":"As manufacturing industry work winds down, education and training jobs wind up","shouldHideAdverts":"false","publication":"theguardian.com","showInRelatedContent":"true","thumbnail":"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2014/6/22/1403422428852/5afa11f7-f407-40e4-a44a-1b1ad0ac906b-140x84.jpeg","wordcount":"934","commentable":"true","internalContentCode":"440114200","allowUgc":"false","internalComposerCode":"53a681bde4b017f323c14121","isPremoderated":"false","byline":"Greg Jericho","internalPageCode":"2114214","productionOffice":"AUS","liveBloggingNow":"false","commentCloseDate":"2014-06-25T17:30:00+10:00"},"webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/business/grogonomics/2014/jun/22/services-sector-jobs-go-ahead-in-leaps-and-bounds-after-mining-boom","apiUrl":"http://beta.content.guardianapis.com/business/grogonomics/2014/jun/22/services-sector-jobs-go-ahead-in-leaps-and-bounds-after-mining-boom","tags":[{"id":"business/grogonomics","webTitle":"Grogonomics","type":"blog","sectionId":"business","sectionName":"Business","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/business/grogonomics","apiUrl":"http://beta.content.guardianapis.com/business/grogonomics","references":[]},{"id":"world/australia-economy","webTitle":"Australia economy","type":"keyword","sectionId":"world","sectionName":"World news","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/world/australia-economy","apiUrl":"http://beta.content.guardianapis.com/world/australia-economy","references":[]},{"id":"world/queensland","webTitle":"Queensland","description":"Latest news and comment on the Australian state of Queensland","type":"keyword","sectionId":"world","sectionName":"World news","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/world/queensland","apiUrl